OLS Regression ¶

We will begin with OLS regression.
Mtcars is one of the default datasets used in R.
The data contains 32 observations and 11 independent variables.
Using the parameters regarding the car models, we will try to estimate the miles per gallon for fuel efficiency.

Variables are defined as follows:

  • mpg - miles per gallon
  • cyl - # of cylinders
  • disp - displacement, in cubic inches
  • hp - horsepower
  • drat - driveshaft ratio
  • wt - weight
  • qsec - 1/4 mile time; a measure of acceleration
  • vs - 'V' or straight - engine shape
  • am - transmission; auto or manual
  • gear - # of gears
  • carb - # of carburetors

Comment:¶

Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) shows that there is a multicollinearity prolem, since most of the VIF values are bigger than or equal to 5.
We will deal with this problem in a bit. Lets check heteroskedasticity of the values.

In [9]:

plt.show()

Comment:¶

It seems that the variation is not a big problem for the error term. Let's use the White Test.

In [10]:
from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import het_white
In [11]:
white_test = het_white(model.resid,  model.model.exog)
In [12]:
labels=("LM Statistic","LM-Test p-value", "F-Statistic", "F-Test p-value")
print(labels, white_test)

('LM Statistic', 'LM-Test p-value', 'F-Statistic', 'F-Test p-value') (32.0, 0.41674402994554294, nan, nan)

Comment:¶

Since the LM-test p-value is larger than 0.05, we are not able to say the variance of the error term is homoskedastic. However, we should also consider other measures before deciding on that.
As discussed earlier, multicollinearity is a big issue and violates the OLS assumption.
So, there are several options to get rid of the multicollinearity problem:

  • transform highly correlated variables
  • drop one of the collinear variables
  • use Lasso or Ridge Regression
  • collect more data etc.

Since we cannot collect more data at this point, we should connsider other methods.
Let's first transform the model from level - level to log - level by taking the logarithm of the dependent variable and see how it works.

Lasso Regression¶

lasso_model

Comment:¶

Alpha or lambda parameter was chosen as 0.01 for the penalty term. Since we know that all variables are insignificant together in the model, all of the beta coefficients are almost equal to zero or zero. Let's find the optimum alpha or lambda parameter.

Here, since we have a small number of independent variables in this model, Lasso regression gives small results. Lasso works better with complex models. Let's try the Ridge regression and see whether it works.

Unfortunately, since the OLS regression coefficient values were small at the first hand, Ridge Regression also gives a bad output, just as Lasso. So, let's use Backward Stepwise Selection and see whether we can drop some variables which cause the multicollinearity problem.

Logistic Regression ¶

Since logistic regression deals with categorical output (binary or multinomial), let's use another dataset here. The dataset is Breast Cancer Wisconsin data from UCI, and aims to determine whether a cancer is malignant or benign.
Variables are defined as follows: 1) ID number
2) Diagnosis (M = malignant, B = benign)
3-32) Ten real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus:

a) radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)
b) texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)
c) perimeter
d) area
e) smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)
f) compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)
g) concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
h) concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
i) symmetry
j) fractal dimension ("coastline approximation" - 1)

Cluster Analysis¶

Cluster analysis is useful when we want to classify the observations when they are homogenous within a group and heterogeneous between each other. For this part, we will examine Violent Crime Rates by US State in 1973 dataset provided by R. The data contains 50 observations and 4 variables which are:

  • murder arrests (per 100,000)
  • assault arrests (per 100,000)
  • urban population
  • rape arrests (per 100,000)

We will try to see whether the states can be grouped regarding the crime rates. Let's load the necessary packages.

Factor Analysis ¶

We have discussed the multicollinearity problem before and tried to solve it by dropping some of the variables or using Lasso & Ridge Regression. Here, we will use another method.
The dataset that we use is a survey of customers regarding car pruchases. There are 90 observations and 14 variables, in which the variables take values of Likert scale from 1 to 5. The variables are as follows:

  • Price
  • Safety
  • Exterior looks
  • Space and comfort
  • Technology
  • After-sales service
  • Resale value
  • Fuel type
  • Fuel efficiency
  • Color
  • Maintenance
  • Test drive
  • Product reviews
  • Testimonials

Let's load our packages and data to begin the analysis.

Decision Trees¶

Decision tree is useful as a nonlinear classifier. They also have no assumptions about the dataset.
Here, we're going to use some Machine Learning Algorithms. We will use Spam Email Database from kernlabs package of R. This dataset includes 4601 observations and 58 variables.

  • The first variables measure the frequency of a variable name such as business in the email.
  • Variables 49-54 incidate the frequency of the charachters other than letters such as exclamation mark.
  • Variables 55 - 57 show measures regarding capital letters.
  • Variable 58 indicates the type of mail as spam or nonspam.

Let's load necessary packages and observe our data.

Comment:¶

The most important indicator of a mail adressed as spam is exclamation mark usage, as seen from the results.

  • word "remove"
  • average # of capital letters

  • word "hp"
  • dollar sign ($)
  • word "george"

to determine whether the mail is spam or not.
